post_text: The East Elementary team has been working diligently to prepare for a safe reopening for the 2020-2021 school year. Our goal is to offer on-campus instruction beginning on August 19, 2020; however, we have developed a remote learning option for parents who may not feel comfortable sending their children to school. Face coverings are highly recommended at this time by the Governors order (Executive Order GA 29) for ages 11 and above. All visitors are required to wear masks and must utilize hand sanitizing stations upon entry. East Elementary students are not required to wear face masks but are allowed to do so if wanted. We ask that if you send your children to class with a face mask, that it is secured to your child. Some examples would be using a lanyard or pacifier clip. We are working to ensure a safe and productive learning environment for all.

post_text:
East Families
Thank you for all your hard work at home teaching and help students to complete their work. To finish out the school year, we have provided a fun bingo board to encourage students to continue growing and learning through the end of the school year and over the summer. Each week, have your child complete a BINGO by choosing 3 activities from the board. Send a short message to your child's teacher celebrating their BINGO. Teachers will still be available for help and support through May 21st.

Remember: Daily reading is the very best way for students to maintain their reading ability over the summer! If your child needs books to read at home, please let us know!

post_text:
We are starting the mindset of "The Time is Now"
Here is the activity that goes with the lesson on "Embrace Every Moment."
Hope you enjoy!

Think about what makes you happy right
now.Today we are going to draw a picture of what makes us happy right now.
Have students draw a picture of what makes them
happy right now.

Challenge:
In this lesson we learned to embrace every
moment and to be happy. I challenge you to focus on
being happy. If someone happens to say something
or do something that makes you sad, try to turn that
frown upside down and find the happy or positive in every day! I will be finding the positive too!

Have a great weekend!
Mrs. Deen

Dear Parents,

In order to keep our staff safe and healthy by limiting the number of papers handled, we are asking that you take a photo of the papers in your packet that will be graded and send it to your teachers Dojo or email account. Your students teacher should have informed you which assignment will be taken for a grade. If you have any questions, please contact the teacher directly.

If you take a picture of the assignment, you will not need to turn in a completed packet. You will need to continue to come pick up the new packets as usual.

If you cannot take a picture and send it to the teacher, we will accept your packet on Monday.

Everyone will still pick up a new packet on Monday anytime from 7:30 - 1:00.

Deen- Counselor
7 Mindsets activity - Live to Give

We have been learning what the Live to Give Mindset means and how we can live it each and every day.
For this activity, we are all going to draw a Giving Tree that shows many different ways to give to another person or cause.
Have students write or draw ways that they can give on the leaves of the tree they drew. Help your child come up with different ways to show a giving nature. Include many ways that do not cost any money.

post_text:
This activity goes with the 7 mindset video.
Making a Difference Project

Brainstorm with your family the ways you can make a difference. It is important for the kids to see that giving to others doesnt mean they have to give or do big things or that it needs to cost money.
Ask your kids: Can you think of a way that you could use one of your talents and something you are good at to help others? (make sure their activity they choose can be done by following the shelter in place and social distancing standards)
Have your child follow through on their idea.
Have your child draw or write about what they did and how it made them feel to make a difference.

post_text:
Here is an activity to go with the 7 mindset lesson.

Activity: Stretch Yourself
Prompt: Lets think about different ways we can make a difference when we Live to Give to others!

Brainstorm with your family about ways you can make a difference. Its important for them to see that giving to others doesnt mean they have to give big things or gifts that cost money.
1. Start the list with examples such as a hug or a smile.
2. Encourage kids to think of small ways to give that are free.

Challenge:
We need to stretch ourselves and try our best in order to live to give. I challenge you to give to someone in your family in an unexpected or small way. Giving can be done many ways, like holding open the door, reading to younger sibling, letting someone else go first, and saying please and thank you.

Prompt: I will be taking this challenge along with you! I can Live to Give when I stretch myself.

East Parents and Guardians,
We had an exciting morning at East. We had a faulty smoke alarm sounding this morning in a classroom. We evacuated the building as a precaution and students and staff did an amazing job of exiting quickly and quietly. Breckenridge Fire Department, BISD Maintenance, and the gas company all came out to check things out and gave us an all-clear.
All is well and we are going to have a great day!

post_text: Kindergarten spies heightened their scientific skills by exploring their 5 senses. Students used their senses as a tool to observe their environment and make observations in 5 Sense Stations. They also got to search for letters and write sight words in shaving cream. In the taste stations, students got to experience the tastes of sour, sweet, bitter and salty. They used their sense of hearing to compare and contrast sounds of animals and listen for beginning sounds. We are teaching great little investigators at East Elementary!!

Teachers are asking that parents bring their childs school supplies at this time. Students who attended East Elementary last year must complete the online returning registration. If you do not have your access code, do not have a home computer or just need help, call or come by East Elementary between 8 and 4. East Elementary will also have a station set up to help out at Meet the Teacher. Students must be registered to receive their schedules.

Thank you!

post_text:
Dear Parents,

In this first week of our study on citizenship, we focused on respecting authority. The students learned what authority means and who authority figures are. They went practiced real life scenarios about respecting authority figures. Our students were not only taught that they should follow the rules and laws, but they should do it with a good attitude. You can further your childs character learning by doing the following at home:

Discussing who are authority figures in your household.

Discussing who are authority figures in your life and how you handle authority as an adult.

Here is the definition of citizenship to review with your child:

Citizenship -

Do your share to make your school and community better

Cooperate

Get involved in community affairs

Stay informed/vote

Be a good neighbor

Obey laws and rules

Respect authority

Protect the environment

volunteer

Have a great weekend!

Shannon Deen

BISD Counselor

Great job to these little leaders!!

post_text:
Dear Parents,
Caring is the character trait we are studying this six weeks. Our students spent this week learning about compassion and discussing how we can show others that we care about them. We also discussed how to be encouraging to our classmates.
At home you can extend this learning by:

Modeling compassion towards others

Having your family write small appreciations on notes to give each other

Planning an act of kindness that your family can do for someone else

Have a great weekend!
Shannon Deen
BISD Counselor

post_text: School will begin at 10:00 am, Tuesday. Water has been restored at East, North, and South Elementary schools. High School and Junior High Buildings do not have water, but the Athletics and Fine Art Center is on a different water line and has water. We will use the restroom facilities at the Athletics Building today. Thanksgiving Lunch is still scheduled at East Elementary at the regularly scheduled time.

post_text:
Dear Parents

Our students are doing a fantastic job showing respect to their friends, their school, and their teachers. I hope they are showing respect at home, as well. Please remind your child that respect means:

1. Treat other with respect - Follow the Golden Rule (treat others the way you want to be treated)

2. Be tolerant and accepting of differences

3. Use good manners

4. Dont use bad language

5. Never threaten, hit or hurt anyone

6. Be considerate of the feelings of others

7. Deal peacefully with anger, insults, and disagreements

Here are a couple ideas on how to incorporate character education at home:

1. Explain the importance of using nice words and actions towards others.

2. Tell your child different words of encouragement that they can use with teammates that show respect.
Great job to these respectful citizens!
